---
import MarketingLayout from "../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro";
---

<MarketingLayout
  title="MailAtlas: local email I/O for AI agents and data apps"
  description="MailAtlas: local email ingestion, export, sending, and audit trails for AI agents and data apps."
>
  <header class="topbar">
    <a class="brand" href="/" aria-label="MailAtlas home">
      <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <span>MailAtlas</span>
    </a>
    <nav class="topnav" aria-label="Primary">
      <a href="#story">How it works</a>
      <a href="#sources">Sources</a>
      <a href="/docs/">Docs</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <main class="landing-main">
    <section class="hero" id="overview">
      <div class="hero-artifact" aria-hidden="true">
        <span>Subject:</span>
        <span>From: alice@example.com</span>
        <span>$ mailatlas ingest</span>
        <span>Content-Type: text/html</span>
        <span>attachment.pdf</span>
        <span>Message-ID:</span>
        <span>mbox://archive.2024</span>
        <span>.eml</span>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">Open-source local email I/O</p>
        <h1>MailAtlas</h1>
        <p class="hero-subhead">Local email I/O for AI agents and data apps.</p>
        <p class="lede">
          MailAtlas turns <code>.eml</code> files, <code>mbox</code> archives, selected IMAP folders,
          and outbound sends into one inspectable workspace on your machine: raw, cleaned, and ready
          to read, query, export, or pipe into your stack.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions" aria-label="Primary actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Start with files</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
        </div>
        <p class="hero-command"><code>python -m pip install mailatlas</code></p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="story">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
        <h2>Three steps. No surprises in between.</h2>
      </div>

      <ol class="step-list">
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Bring email in</h3>
            <p>
              Point MailAtlas at saved <code>.eml</code> files, an <code>mbox</code> archive, or a
              selected IMAP folder. The workspace stays local and visible.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Keep provenance attached</h3>
            <p>
              Raw bytes stay linked to cleaned text, normalized HTML, inline images, attachments,
              metadata, and outbound send records.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Export or build on it</h3>
            <p>
              Read the workspace directly, or export JSON, Markdown, HTML, and optional PDF for
              agents, notebooks, search indexes, audits, or your own pipeline.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="sources">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Sources and sinks</p>
        <h2>Choose where your email lives.</h2>
        <p>
          Start with one path and add others later. Everything lands in the same local MailAtlas
          workspace.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list">
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">
          <strong>Files</strong>
          <span>Drop individual messages or folders of exported email.</span>
          <code>.eml</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/examples/mbox-ingest/">
          <strong>Archive</strong>
          <span>Ingest historical mailbox exports without flattening the source.</span>
          <code>mbox</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">
          <strong>Mailbox</strong>
          <span>Fetch selected IMAP folders on demand into the local store.</span>
          <code>sync</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">
          <strong>Outbound</strong>
          <span>Send through SMTP, Cloudflare, or Gmail and keep a local audit record.</span>
          <code>send</code>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="try">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Try it</p>
        <h2>From zero to your first ingested message.</h2>
        <p>A virtualenv, an install, a home directory, and one ingest. That is the warm-up.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="terminal">
        <div class="terminal-bar">
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <code>~/work</code>
        </div>
        <pre><code>python3.12 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
python -m pip install mailatlas
export MAILATLAS_HOME="$PWD/.mailatlas"

mailatlas ingest path/to/message.eml
mailatlas list</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-fit" id="fit">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Is it for you?</p>
        <h2>Built for a specific job. Honest about the rest.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="fit-stack">
        <article>
          <h3>Reach for it when</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You are feeding email into an AI agent, retrieval system, notebook, or data app.</li>
            <li>You need raw, cleaned, and structured views of the same message.</li>
            <li>You want to script over years of <code>mbox</code> or <code>.eml</code> without a server.</li>
            <li>You need a local audit trail for email your app sends out.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article>
          <h3>It is not</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>A hosted inbox or webmail client.</li>
            <li>A managed connector or integration service.</li>
            <li>A deliverability or marketing platform.</li>
            <li>A replacement for your mail server.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="footer-cta">
      <div class="footer-brand">
        <a class="brand" href="/" aria-label="MailAtlas home">
          <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>MailAtlas</span>
        </a>
        <p>Open-source local email I/O. Read the docs, install it, and keep your mail where you can see it.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="mailto:hello@mailatlas.dev">hello@mailatlas.dev</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <nav class="footer-links" aria-label="Footer">
        <div>
          <h2>Docs</h2>
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Quickstart</a>
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">IMAP sync</a>
          <a href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">Outbound</a>
          <a href="/docs/concepts/document-schema/">Schema</a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Project</h2>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/examples">Examples</a>
          <a href="/docs/marketing/roadmap/">Roadmap</a>
          <a href="/docs/marketing/product-vision/">Vision</a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Contact</h2>
          <a href="mailto:hello@mailatlas.dev">hello@mailatlas.dev</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas/issues">Issues</a>
        </div>
      </nav>

      <div class="footer-bottom">
        <span>© 2026 MailAtlas. MIT licensed.</span>
        <span>local-first</span>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </main>
</MarketingLayout>
